## Phase 5 — Database & Performance

### 1. Schema Deep Dive (`Game.model.ts`)
Your `Game` schema is a massive document. It contains an array of `players` (`IPlayerState`). 
In MongoDB, storing players *inside* the Game document is called **Embedding**. It is perfect for this game because you always need the players when you fetch the game, and games are ephemeral (they end in 15 minutes).

### 2. Indexing
In `Game.model.ts`, you have `roomCode: { type: String, unique: true }`. 
MongoDB automatically creates an **Index** on this. An index is like the table of contents in a book. When a user tries to join room "ABCD", Mongo doesn't scan millions of games; it jumps straight to "ABCD".

### 3. Why Queries Get Slow
Updating `sharedCode` every single keystroke to MongoDB is an anti-pattern. Databases write to physical SSDs. 
*Better Approach:* Accumulate code changes in Server Memory (RAM) using variables, and only save to MongoDB every 5 seconds (Throttling/Debouncing), or when the game ends.

